INSERT INTO `artists` VALUES (1,'Tim Britton','2015-02-24 18:28:41','2015-03-19 20:03:34','tim-britton','<p>Tim Britton is an Iowa-based musician known for his skills on the uilleann pipes, in addition to the wooden flute, tin whistle, Highland pipes, and mandolin. He is also a singer and storyteller. He was exposed to the folk music scene in the 1960s through his parents George and Charlotte, a folk singer and talent agent, respectively. The Britton Folk Studio was a successful folk music school. As a child, Britton became interested in his Celtic heritage, researching various aspects of culture, music, and history. His involvement in the Philadelphia Irish Center nurtured his dance and musical abilities. He also learned the art of pipemaking. In the course of his career Britton has performed both domestically and internationally, as a solo artist and in collaboration with other musicians, in concert and on the radio. In addition to performing and pipemaking, he also writes, teaches workshops, and engineers recordings.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'tim_britton_aia_031.003-031-016.jpg','image/jpeg',55627,'2015-03-19 20:03:34','<p>Tim Britton, circa 1970-1979; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 31, Folder 16; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(2,'Liz Carroll','2015-02-24 18:34:47','2015-03-19 20:04:41','liz-carroll','<p>Liz Carroll (1956 - ) is a Chicago-based musician of Irish descent. In 1974 she won the All-Ireland under-18 fiddle championship, winning the All-Ireland Senior Fiddle Championship the following year. She has performed as both a solo artists and member of ensembles, including The Green Fields of America and String Sisters. Carroll has been featured on numerous albums, as well as her own solo records. She received the National Endowment for the Arts&rsquo; National Heritage Fellowship Award in 1994, and in 2010 became the first Irish American musician nominated for a Grammy Award for her recording <em>Double Play</em> with John Doyle in the &ldquo;Best Traditional World Music Album&rdquo; category. 200 of her compositions were published in 2010 as <em>Collected: Original Irish Tunes</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'liz_carroll_aia_031.003-031-024.jpg','image/jpeg',25443,'2015-03-19 20:04:41','<p>Liz Carroll, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 31, Folder 23; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(3,'Father Charlie Coen','2015-02-24 18:36:12','2015-03-19 20:05:13','father-charlie-coen','<p>Father Charlie Coen was born in Woodford, County Galway in 1933 and emigrated to the United States in 1955. In addition to serving as the pastor of St. Joseph and St. Thomas parishes in Staten Island, Coen is also an accomplished musician, known for his <em>sean-n&oacute;s</em>&nbsp;singing, and skills on the concertina, flute, and tin whistle. He has won All-Ireland Championships in all four categories. He became Monsignor Coen in 2006 and retired from his parish post in 2008.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'fr_charlie_coen_aia_031.003-031-039.jpg','image/jpeg',29319,'2015-03-19 20:05:13','<p>Father&nbsp;Charlie Coen, 1979; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 31, Folder 39; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(4,'Father Charlie Coen’s Children’s Choir','2015-02-24 18:37:43','2015-03-19 20:06:30','father-charlie-coen-s-children-s-choir','<p>Fr. Charlie Coen&rsquo;s Children&rsquo;s Choir was a small musical ensemble of singers from the St. Joseph and St. Thomas parishes in Long Island.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'fr_charlie_coens_childrens_choir_aia_031.003-031-040.jpg','image/jpeg',33889,'2015-03-19 20:06:30','<p>Father Charlie Coen&rsquo;s Children&#39;s Choir, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 31, Folder 40; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(5,'James Keane','2015-02-24 18:38:38','2015-03-19 20:06:50','james-keane','<p>James Keane (1948 - ) is an Irish traditional musician known for his accordion playing. He was born in Drimnagh in Co. Dublin to parents who were both fiddle players and who frequently hosted travelling musicians performing in the city. The musical upbringing nurtured Keane&rsquo;s abilities and by the age of ten he was a fixture in the 1950s Dublin traditional music scene. In his teens he helped found the Castle C&eacute;il&iacute; Band, which went on to win numerous Oireachtas competitions and the All-Ireland Senior C&eacute;il&iacute; Band competition in 1965. He won many competitions for his accordion playing. Keane later emigrated to the United States where he played with numerous ensembles, including the Ellis Island C&eacute;il&iacute; Band and Fingal. In addition to performing, Keane also teaches on the history of Irish traditional music.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'james_keane_aia_031.003-031-117.jpg','image/jpeg',33467,'2015-03-19 20:06:50','<p>James Keane, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 31, Folder 117; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(6,'Billy McComiskey','2015-02-24 18:39:36','2015-02-24 18:39:36','billy-mccomiskey','<p>Billy McComiskey (1951 - ) is an Irish American musician known for his button accordion playing. Born in Brooklyn, McComiskey has been instrumental in the development of the traditional music scene in the Baltimore and Washington area. Some of his better known compositions include &ldquo;The Controversial Reel&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Commodore.&rdquo; He began playing with his mentor Sean McGlynn at the age of 15, where he learned from McGlynn&rsquo;s East Galway accordion style. McComiskey has played with numerous Irish and American musicians, including the trios Irish Tradition and Trian. In 1986, McComiskey won the All-Ireland Championship for the button accordion.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,''),(7,'Eleanor Kane Neary','2015-02-24 18:40:25','2015-02-24 18:40:25','eleanor-kane-neary','<p>Eleanor Kane Neary (1918 &ndash; 1993) was an Irish American piano player from the South Side of Chicago. Eleanor and her husband, fiddler Jimmy Neary, were influential members of the Irish traditional music scene in Chicago from the 1930s through the 1980s. The Neary house was often a gathering point for local and travelling musicians. Although a prolific performer, she recorded very seldom.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,''),(8,'Andy O’Brien','2015-02-24 18:40:57','2015-02-24 18:40:57','andy-o-brien','<p>Andy O&rsquo;Brien is an Irish born guitarist and singer from Co. Kerry who often played as a member of the ensemble Irish Tradition with Billy McComiskey and Brendan Mulvihill.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,''),(9,'Robbie O’Connell','2015-02-24 18:41:46','2015-03-19 20:07:14','robbie-o-connell','<p>Robbie O&rsquo;Connell (1951 - ) is an Irish born singer and songwriter known for his solo performing and his collaborations with The Clancy Brothers. Born in Waterford, O&rsquo;Connell grew up in Carrick-on-Suir, Co. Tipperary and toured folk music clubs in England prior to studying literature and philosophy at University College Dublin. O&rsquo;Connell toured and performed with various groups in the 1970s, including The Munster Cloak and The Bread and Beer Band. He also frequently toured with his family members in The Clancy Brothers. In 1979 O&rsquo;Connell and his family moved to Franklin, Massachusetts. He released his first solo album, <em>Close to the Bone</em>, in 1982. O&rsquo;Connell frequently performed and toured with Mick Moloney, Jimmy Keane, and the members of the Green Fields of America. Liam Clancy and O&rsquo;Connell later toured as a duo, eventually adding Liam&rsquo;s son Donal to the group.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'robbie_o\'connell_aia_031.003-032-055.jpg','image/jpeg',35891,'2015-03-19 20:07:14','<p>Robbie O&rsquo;Connell, circa 1980-1989; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 32, Folder 55; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(10,'Eugene O’Donnell','2015-02-24 18:42:32','2015-03-19 20:07:36','eugene-o-donnell','<p>Eugene O&rsquo;Donnell (1932 - ) is an Irish-born fiddler living in Philadelphia. He was born in Co. Derry to parents from Co. Donegal, which helped form his connection to Irish musical traditions. In addition to his skills on the fiddle, O&rsquo; Donnell is also a five-time All-Ireland Step Dance champion. He often plays with Mick Moloney.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'eugene_o\'donnell_aia_031.003-032-059.jpg','image/jpeg',43094,'2015-03-19 20:07:36','<p>Eugene O&rsquo;Donnell, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 32, Folder 59; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(11,'Jerry O’Sullivan','2015-02-24 18:43:13','2015-03-19 20:10:06','jerry-o-sullivan','<p>Jerry O&rsquo;Sullivan is an Irish American musician, specializing in the uilleann pipes. He was a member of the ensemble the Green Fields of America during the 1980s, and has played alongside numerous musicians, including Eileen Ivers, Susan McKeown, and even Dolly Parton. O&rsquo;Sullivan has recorded three solo albums.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'jerry_o\'sullivan_aia_031.003-043-063.jpg','image/jpeg',67377,'2015-03-19 20:10:06','<p>Jerry O&rsquo;Sulivan, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 32, Folder 63; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(12,'Ed Reavy','2015-02-24 18:43:56','2015-03-19 20:10:41','ed-reavy','<p>Ed Reavy (1897 &ndash; 1988) was an Irish born fiddler who emigrated to the United States and became an integral part of the Philadelphia traditional music scene. Born in Barnagrove, Co. Cavan, Reavy moved to the Corktown neighborhood of Philadelphia in 1912. A prolific performer, Reavy&rsquo;s may be best known for his tune &ldquo;The Hunter&rsquo;s House.&rdquo; At one point he served as the president of the Irish Musicians&rsquo; Association of America.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'ed_reavy.jpg','image/jpeg',36598,'2015-03-19 20:10:41','<p>Ed Reavy, undated; Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Personal Papers; AIA 031.003; Box 33, Folder 13; Archives of Irish America; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University</p>\r\n'),(13,'Frank Thornton','2015-02-24 18:44:35','2015-02-24 18:44:35','frank-thornton','<p>Frank Thornton (1908 &ndash; 1997) was an Irish born musician, Chicago police officer, and founding member of Comhaltas, an organization devoted to the preservation and promotion of Irish traditional music. Thornton was born in Kilbaha in Co. Kerry and emigrated to the United States in 1929. From 1938 until 1965, Thornton was a member of the Chicago Police Department. A skilled flute and tin whistle player, Thornton taught lessons and performed frequently, forming the Thornton Fife and Drum Band and touring Ireland with other Chicago-area musicians. In 1956, along with Ed Reavy, Louis E. Quinn, and Johnny McGreevy, Thornton helped found the Irish Musicians&rsquo; Association of America in order to establish a more unified network of musicians playing traditional Irish music. He served as the organization&rsquo;s first president.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,''),(14,'Kevin Henry','2015-02-24 18:45:07','2015-03-19 20:11:38','kevin-henry','<p>Kevin Henry (1929 - ) is an Irish born musician, actor, storyteller, and former ironworker known for his skills with multiple instruments, including the flute, tin whistle, and uilleann pipes. Henry was born near Tubbercurry in Co. Sligo close to the Co. Mayo border. He worked in England prior to emigrating to Chicago, where he became an ironworker in the city&rsquo;s construction industry. Henry has been a frequent performer in the Chicago area, joining the city&rsquo;s Irish Guild Players and in 1956, becoming a founding member of the Chicago chapter of the Irish Musicians&rsquo; Association.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'kevin_henry.jpg','image/jpeg',39476,'2015-03-19 20:11:38',''),(15,'Pat Roche','2015-02-24 18:45:50','2015-02-24 18:45:50','pat-roche','<p>Pat Roche (1905 &ndash; 2004) was an Irish dancer and dance teacher from Co. Clare who was a prominent member of the Irish musical and cultural community in Chicago and an influential figure in the development of Irish dancing in America. While a boy in Ireland, he became the student of traveling dance master Michael Hennessy. In 1925 Roche emigrated to New York, where he lived for five years before moving to Chicago. He was the founder and president of the Roche School of Irish Dancing, the host of an Irish radio show, and the former editor of the <em>American Gael</em> newspaper.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,''),(16,'Terry “Cuz” Teahan','2015-02-24 18:46:33','2015-03-19 20:04:14','terry-cuz-teahan','<p>Terry &ldquo;Cuz&rdquo; Teahan (1905 &ndash; 1989) was an Irish born musician prominent in the Chicago traditional music scene. Skilled in multiple instruments, Teahan played the fiddle, concertina, and accordion.</p>\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'terry_teahan.jpg','image/jpeg',53790,'2015-03-19 20:04:14','');
